# Environment variables read by app.py.
# Copy this file to `/etc/ssr.env` on the server and edit.
# systemd unit (setup/ssr-dashboard.service) reads from /etc/ssr.env via EnvironmentFile=.

# --- Network binding ---
# Default (unset): 127.0.0.1 only. The systemd setup binds this way and
# fronts with nginx for TLS + rate-limiting.
# Set to 1 ONLY if you know you want to expose the dashboard on all interfaces.
# SSR_BIND_ALL=1

# --- Reverse-proxy awareness ---
# Set to 1 when Flask is behind nginx / cloudflare / any reverse proxy.
# Enables werkzeug ProxyFix so request.remote_addr == the real client IP
# (needed for per-IP login throttle and rate limits).
SSR_BEHIND_PROXY=1

# --- HTTPS hardening ---
# Set to 1 when terminating TLS in front of Flask. Enables:
#   - Secure cookie flag
#   - HSTS response header (1 year)
SSR_HTTPS_ONLY=1

# --- Debug mode ---
# Do NOT set in production. Enables Flask debug mode (tracebacks in browser,
# auto-reloader) — only useful during local development.
# SSR_DEBUG=1

# --- Job-queue worker pool size ---
# How many in-process worker threads claim jobs from the durable queue
# (see modules/jobs.py / template_v0/lib/jobs.ts). Default 4. Bumping raises
# pipeline parallelism but also raises the rate at which this process hits
# CF / DO / SA APIs. Tune to your account quotas. Bulk-pipeline jobs always
# serialize through a single bulk handler, regardless of pool size.
#
# IMPORTANT: only ONE worker pool should claim jobs at a time. If you run
# both `python app.py` AND the Next.js dashboard, set this to 0 on whichever
# side you don't want to own the queue.
# SSR_JOB_WORKERS=4

# --- Smooth-running 50-concurrent profile ---
# Recommended config when fanning out ~50 pipelines simultaneously.
# (For light dev use, leave these unset and the defaults take over.)
#
# SSR_JOB_WORKERS=50            # one worker per concurrent pipeline
# SSR_CHROMIUM_CONCURRENCY=4    # cap on simultaneous patchright browsers
#                               # (each is ~300 MB; uncapped 50 = 15 GB peak)
# SSR_LLM_CONCURRENCY=8         # cap on concurrent Anthropic LLM calls
#                               # (avoids per-account TPM bursts → 429s)
# SSR_CF_CONCURRENCY=5          # cap on concurrent CF API calls PER KEY
#                               # (each cf_email gets its own queue at this
#                               # cap; keeps step-7's DNS-setup burst from
#                               # tripping per-account rate limits even when
#                               # 50 pipelines fan out across 10 keys)
# SSR_AUTOHEAL_INTERVAL_MS=300000   # 5 min default; raise to 600000 (10 min)
#                                   # if you don't want auto-heal competing
#                                   # for SA/CF API budget while a fan-out is
#                                   # in flight.
# SSR_AUTOHEAL=0                # Disable auto-heal entirely during a planned
#                               # large fan-out, then re-enable after.
#
# For real load, run prod mode (much leaner than `next dev`):
#   cd template_v0
#   npm run build
#   SSR_JOB_WORKERS=50 SSR_CHROMIUM_CONCURRENCY=4 SSR_LLM_CONCURRENCY=8 \
#       npm run start

# --- API failover (DigitalOcean + ServerAvatar) ---
# Both providers support primary + backup token failover. When the primary
# returns 401 / 403 / 429 / 5xx OR times out, calls automatically retry on
# the backup token. Use this to survive a suspended / rate-limited account
# mid-migration without operator intervention.
#
# Configure in /settings — these env vars are read for diagnostic / audit
# purposes; the live values come from the DB so the dashboard can rotate
# them without a restart.
#
# DigitalOcean settings keys:    do_api_token, do_api_token_backup, do_use_backup_first
# ServerAvatar settings keys:    serveravatar_api_key, serveravatar_api_key_backup
# ServerAvatar org settings:     serveravatar_org_id, serveravatar_org_id_backup

# --- Database path ---
# Where lib/db.ts looks for the shared SQLite file. If unset it resolves
# to ../data/ssr.db relative to template_v0's cwd. Set this when running
# the Next.js dashboard from a non-default location (e.g. systemd cwd).
# SSR_DB_PATH=/var/lib/ssr/ssr.db
